INTRODUCTION AND READING OF BILLS

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Education
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to requiring the reporting of environmental data regarding schools.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring the reporting of environmental data regarding schools.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Housing and Buildings
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the New York State Legislature to pass and the Governor to enact a law that would grant the City of New York the authority to levy a school impact tax on developers of new or converted non-senior housing on a per-unit basis, to be administered by the New York City Department of Buildings at the time of filing for a certificate of occupancy for such housing, for the purpose of providing funding for the construction of new public K-12 schools, and that such tax be specifically designated for the construction of such schools.
EventItemMatterName: Grant NYC the authority to levy a school impact tax on developers of new or converted non-senior housing on a per-unit basis.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on State and Federal Legislation
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the United States Congress to pass and the President to sign into law the Puppy Uniform Protection and Safety Act (S.395/H.R.847), which would require commercial breeders who sell their puppies directly to the public, including via the Internet, to be licensed and inspected by the United States Department of Agriculture and mandate that commercial breeding facilities provide dogs with daily exercise.
EventItemMatterName: Puppy Uniform Protection and Safety Act (S.395/H.R.847)

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Veterans
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the New York State Legislature to pass, and the Governor to sign, A.514/S.3872, legislation which would amend the Real Property Tax Law to allow veterans in New York City to enjoy the full value of the Veterans’ Property Tax Exemption.
EventItemMatterName: Allow veterans in NYC to enjoy the full value of the Veterans’ Property Tax Exemption. (A.514/S.3872)

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Education
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the Chancellor of the New York City Department of Education to institute a daily moment of silence in all New York City public schools.
EventItemMatterName: Dept of Education to institute a daily moment of silence in all NYC public schools.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the New York city charter, in relation to reporting tribunal outcomes.
EventItemMatterName: Reporting tribunal outcomes.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to daylight saving time.
EventItemMatterName: Daylight saving time.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the United States Congress to pass and the President to sign into law an amendment to the Help America Vote Act which would allow the use of lever machines in federal elections.
EventItemMatterName: Help America Vote Act

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the State University of New York and the New York State Department of Health to work with stakeholders to pursue the acquisition of Long Island College Hospital (LICH) by another health care institution to preserve critical health care services for the community, and to ensure that all resources gained from any sale or transfer of LICH assets are used exclusively for the preservation of these services; and authorizing the Speaker to file or join amicus briefs on behalf of the Council in support of the preservation of such services.
EventItemMatterName: State University of NY and the NYS Dept of Health to work with stakeholders to pursue the acquisition of Long Island College Hospital (LICH).

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Contracts
EventItemTitle: Resolution adopting the rule amendment of the Procurement Policy Board to raise the micropurchase limit to $20,000.
EventItemMatterName: Adopting the rule amendment of the Procurement Policy Board to raise the micropurchase limit to $20,000.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Finance
EventItemTitle: Resolution approving the granting of an exemption for real property taxes pursuant to section 420-a of the Real Property Tax Law, for the 2003 through 2008  assessment rolls for the parcel owned by the Foundation for Sephardic Studies, Inc. in the City of New York, borough of Brooklyn, designated on the tax map as block 07089, lot 07  in such borough, and the cancellation of  taxes, fines, penalties and interest remaining unpaid, and the making of appropriate correction of the subject assessment rolls, if, upon  accepting and reviewing the application or renewal application for such exemption, the Department of Finance is satisfied that such corporation would otherwise be entitled to such exemption if it had filed such application for exemption by the appropriate taxable status date, in accordance with, and upon the effective date of, the chapter law represented by Assembly Bill A. 7153.
EventItemMatterName: Approving the granting of an exemption for real property taxes pursuant to section 420-a of the Real Property Tax Law. (A.6706)

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Consumer Affairs
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to the review and approval of petitions for revocable consents to operate sidewalk cafes.
EventItemMatterName: Review and approval of petitions for revocable consents to operate sidewalk cafes.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Civil Service and Labor
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the United States Department of Labor to assume the cost of all Hurricane Sandy related unemployment claims through the Federal Disaster Unemployment Assistance Program and on the New York State Department of Labor to exempt businesses from paying unemployment claims due to Hurricane Sandy and all future disasters.
EventItemMatterName: Dept of Labor to assume the cost of all Hurricane Sandy related unemployment claims through the Federal Disaster Unemployment Assistance Program.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Contracts
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to the creation of a database to track the expenditure of funds in connection with recovery efforts in the wake of Hurricane Sandy.
EventItemMatterName: Creation of a database to track the expenditure of funds in connection with recovery efforts in the wake of Hurricane Sandy.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Education
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the New York city charter, in relation to requiring the department of education, in consultation with the New York city police department, to provide additional security measures in public schools.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring the department of education, in consultation with the NYPD, to provide additional security measures in public schools.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Finance
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the New York State Legislature to introduce and pass, and the Governor to sign, legislation which would allow a tax credit for business owners who employ individuals who have been unemployed for at least six months.
EventItemMatterName: Allow a tax credit for business owners who employ individuals who have been unemployed for at least six months.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Public Safety
EventItemTitle: Resolution recognizing June as Gun Violence Awareness Month in New York City.
EventItemMatterName: Recognizing June as Gun Violence Awareness Month in NYC.
